TY  - JOUR
T1  - Order without law? the role of certified management standards in shaping socially desired firm behaviors
AU  - Terlaak, Ann
Y1  - 2007/07/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.25275685
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.25275685
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 968
EP  - 985
VL  - 32
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Certified management standards (CMS), like norms, rely on decentralized enforcement processes to guide firm behaviors. I analyze how two elements of CMS?codification and certification?enable this institution to shape firm behaviors in settings where norms are ineffective. I further theorize that these same two elements limit the effectiveness of CMS by weakening enforcement processes. I contribute to institutional theory by identifying possibilities and limitations for normlike institutions to function beyond established boundary conditions.
AB  - Certified management standards (CMS), like norms, rely on decentralized enforcement processes to guide firm behaviors. I analyze how two elements of CMS?codification and certification?enable this institution to shape firm behaviors in settings where norms are ineffective. I further theorize that these same two elements limit the effectiveness of CMS by weakening enforcement processes. I contribute to institutional theory by identifying possibilities and limitations for normlike institutions to function beyond established boundary conditions.
