TY  - JOUR
T1  - Absorptive capacity: Valuing a reconceptualization
AU  - Todorova, Gergana
AU  - Durisin, Boris
Y1  - 2007/07/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.25275513
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.25275513
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 774
EP  - 786
VL  - 32
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Zahra and George (2002) suggested a reconceptualization of the absorptive capacity construct in order to reduce ambiguity in empirical studies. A rereading of the seminal Cohen and Levinthal (1990) article in light of current research on learning and innovation directs our attention to serious ambiguities and omissions in Zahra and George's reconceptualization. We suggest a reintroduction of ?recognizing the value,? an alternative understanding of ?transformation,? a clarification of ?potential absorptive capacity,? an elaboration of the impact of socialization mechanisms, an investigation of the role of ?power relationships,? and an inclusion of feedback loops in a dynamic model of absorptive capacity.
AB  - Zahra and George (2002) suggested a reconceptualization of the absorptive capacity construct in order to reduce ambiguity in empirical studies. A rereading of the seminal Cohen and Levinthal (1990) article in light of current research on learning and innovation directs our attention to serious ambiguities and omissions in Zahra and George's reconceptualization. We suggest a reintroduction of ?recognizing the value,? an alternative understanding of ?transformation,? a clarification of ?potential absorptive capacity,? an elaboration of the impact of socialization mechanisms, an investigation of the role of ?power relationships,? and an inclusion of feedback loops in a dynamic model of absorptive capacity.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.25275513
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2007.25275513
Y2  - 2026/04/24
