T1  - Crossing the line(s): A dual threshold model of anger in organizations
AU  - Geddes, Deanna
AU  - Callister, Ronda Roberts
Y1  - 2007/07/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.25275495
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.25275495
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 721
EP  - 746
VL  - 32
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We present a theoretical model of contextualized anger expression to challenge prominent antisocial, aggression, and individual actor perspectives reflected in the current literature, and we assert that organizational observers' judgments and reactions help determine whether anger results in more negative or positive outcomes. The dual threshold model includes an expression threshold, which is crossed when individuals communicate rather than suppress anger, and an impropriety threshold, which is crossed if expressed anger violates organizational emotion display norms.
AB  - We present a theoretical model of contextualized anger expression to challenge prominent antisocial, aggression, and individual actor perspectives reflected in the current literature, and we assert that organizational observers' judgments and reactions help determine whether anger results in more negative or positive outcomes. The dual threshold model includes an expression threshold, which is crossed when individuals communicate rather than suppress anger, and an impropriety threshold, which is crossed if expressed anger violates organizational emotion display norms.
